        "content": "<p>I just reviewed <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/18188\">#18188</a>. The proof is good (one lemma, five lines of proof), but I wonder if a slightly different (shorter) route is preferrable. Style opinions on which version is preferred are welcome.</p>",
        "id": 478768156,
        "sender_full_name": "Michael Rothgang",
        "timestamp": 1729791379
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My general opinion is that full term-mode is preferred for very short proofs (one or two lines at most), while readable tactics are preferred everywhere else</p>",
        "id": 478770253,
        "sender_full_name": "Violeta Hernández",
        "timestamp": 1729792306
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My opinion is that:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>I'm not sure why we want this lemma at all.</li>\n<li>If we did, I'd go with this proof (note that it uses the lemma which I think is actually more useful):</li>\n</ol>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Topology</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Separation</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">t2Space_antitone</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Antitone</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"bp\">@</span><span class=\"n\">T2Space</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">X</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"k\">fun</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">inst₁</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">inst₂</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h_top</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h_t2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↦</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">@</span><span class=\"n\">T2Space</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">of_injective_continuous</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">inst₁</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">inst₂</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"n\">h_t2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">_</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Function</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">injective_id</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">&lt;|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">continuous_id_of_le</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h_top</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Of course, there may be even better proofs than this.</p>",
